FOOT & MOUTH DISEASE - NAMIBIA: (ZAMBEZI) BOVINE, NOT TYPED, OIE
****************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Mon 17 Jul 2017
Source: OIE, WAHID (World Animal Health Information Database), weekly disease information 2017; 30(29) [edited]
http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review?page_refer=MapFullEventReport&reportid=24324


Foot-and-mouth disease, Namibia
-------------------------------
Information received on [and dated] 17 Jul 2017 from Dr Adrianatus Florentius Maseke, Chief Veterinary Officer, Veterinary Services, Ministry of Agriculture, Water and Forestry, Windhoek, Namibia

Summary
Report type: immediate notification
Date of start of the event: 12 Jul 2017
Date of confirmation of the event: 14 Jul 2017
Reason for notification: recurrence of a listed disease
Date of previous occurrence: 25 Jan 2016
Manifestation of disease: clinical disease
Causal agent: Foot and mouth disease virus
Serotype: not typed
Nature of diagnosis: clinical, laboratory (basic)
This event pertains to a defined zone within the country.

New outbreaks (1)
Summary of outbreaks:
Total outbreaks: 1
Outbreak 1: Musele Island-Kasika Crushpen, Katima-Mulilo, Katima-Mulilo, Zambezi
Date of start of the outbreak: 12 Jul 2017
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not provided)
Epidemiological unit: village
Total animals affected:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Killed and disposed of / Slaughtered
Cattle / 400 / 9 / 0 / 0 / 0
Outbreak statistics [rates apparent, expressed as percentages]
Species / Morbidity rate / Mortality rate / Case fatality rate / Proportion susceptible animals lost*
Cattle / 2.25 / 0 / 0 / 0
*Removed from the susceptible population through death, destruction, and/or slaughter

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: contact with wild species.
Epidemiological comment: animals showing pathognomonic signs of FMD ranging from ulcers on dental pad, muzzle, inter-digital space, and coronary bands. Ulcers range from stages of early healing, advanced healing to the stage of complete healing.

Control measures
Measures applied: movement control inside the country, surveillance within containment and/or protection zone, traceability, quarantine, disinfection, vaccination permitted (if a vaccine exists), no treatment of affected animals
Measures to be applied: vaccination in response to the outbreak (s)

Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type / Species / Test / Test date / Result
Central Veterinary Laboratory (national laboratory) / Cattle / Non-structural protein ELISA / 14 Jul 2017/ Positive
Central Veterinary Laboratory (national laboratory) / Cattle / real-time PCR / 14 Jul 2017/ Positive

Future reporting
The event is continuing. Weekly follow-up reports will be submitted.

[The location of the outbreak can be seen on the interactive map included in the OIE report at the source URL above.]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The previous FMD event in the Zambezi region was reported in July 2015, where the serotype SAT1 was identified in 2 outbreaks. The event was resolved in January 2016. See a summary and updated map of this event at: http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review?reportid=19613. - Mod.CRD

